together diverse case studies, integrating analysis of class, age, gender, sexuality, and race into the scholarship. Essays span the United States and Canadian border, exploring gender violence, sexual harassment, the violent kidnapping of union organizers, the violence of inadequate health and safety protections, the culture of violence in state institutions, the mythology of working-class violence, and the changing nature of violence in extractive industries. The Violence of Work theorizes and historicizes violence as an integral part of working life, making it possible to understand the full scope and causes of workplace violence over time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aLaborzCanadaxHistory. 0aLaborzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aViolence in the workplacexSocial aspectszCanadaxHistory. 0aViolence in the workplacexSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aViolencexSocial aspectszCanadaxHistory. 0aViolencexSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aWorking classzCanadaxSocial conditions. 0aWorking classzUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 7aHISTORY / Essays.2bisacsh  aNorth America.  acapitalism.  ahistory of violence.  ahistory of work.  alabor history.  alabour history.  alabour violence.  asex work.  astrip mining.  aviolence at work.  aviolence studies.  aworkplace injury.  aworkplace violence.1 aGoings, Aaron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJessup, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLb. Twarog, Emily E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMilloy, Jeremy , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMilloy, Jeremy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPearson, Chad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/v